                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3891271d/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>salary, which was generally 3 quarters in amount, and was\n                                        content<lb/> to receive it in any manner, taking whatever\n                                        was offered me, which was<lb/> not unfrequently 20 dollars\n                                        at a time! But it was useless. An<lb/> angel from Heaven\n                                        would not satisfy them, and I, who possess<lb/> no angelic\n                                        quality of course found it beyond my capability. To<lb/>\n                                        enumerate the indignities I suffered would fill a volume;\n                                        and<lb/> I endured them patiently till threatened with\n                                        personal violence.<lb/> It was time to resign; and as\n                                                  <placeName>St. Thomas</placeName> presented less\n                                        advantages<lb/> than <placeName>Kingston</placeName>, behold\n                                        me here again, welcomed with an intensity<lb/> of feeling I\n                                        was unprepared for, and what is more, with expressions<lb/>\n                                        of profound regret that I ever left. My impression always\n                                        was,<lb/> that neither by preparatory study nor habits,\n                                        inclination, or temper<lb/> was I ever intended or\n                                                  <sic>capacitated</sic> to minister before the<lb/>\n                                        Lord; circumstances forced the situation on me; and\n                                        now,<lb/> having, without the needful qualifications, gained\n                                        a reputation<lb/> I am unwilling to damage it by continuing\n                                        in a profession<lb/> where there are so many candidates\n                                        better adapted to supply<lb/> vacancies than myself. I am\n                                        not ignorant that the Congregation<lb/> in <placeName>N.\n                                                  O.</placeName> give me the preference to any\n                                        other; this is flattering to my<lb/> feelings, an unction to\n                                        my vanity if you like, but for my own<lb/> part, the course\n                                        I have pursued in declining the appointment,<lb/> must,\n                                        after this candid avowal, be deemed satisfactory by\n                                        you.<lb/> I have now unbosomed myself, and shall be glad to\n                                        hear<lb/> your opinion, as I always set the highest value,\n                                        on whatever<lb/> emanated from you.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">I need not say how delighted I shall<lb/> be to\n                                        hear from <persName>Miss DeCordova</persName> her estimate\n                                        of my obt friend</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3891271d/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
            }
